#: ../../content/developer/reference/frontend/error_handling.rst:346
msgid "Errors are expensive"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/developer/reference/frontend/error_handling.rst:348
msgid "Because errors need to unwind the callstack and collect information as they do so, throwing errors is slow. Additionally, JavaScript runtimes are generally optimized with the assumption that exceptions are rare, and as such generally compiles the code with the assumption that it doesn't throw, and fall back to a slower code path if it ever does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/developer/reference/frontend/error_handling.rst:355
msgid "Throwing errors makes debugging harder"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/developer/reference/frontend/error_handling.rst:357
msgid "JavaScript debuggers, like the one included in the Chrome and Firefox devtools for example, have a feature that allows you to pause the execution when an exception is thrown. You can also choose whether to pause only on caught exceptions, or on both caught and uncaught exceptions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/developer/reference/frontend/error_handling.rst:362
msgid "When you throw an error inside of code that is called by Owl or by the JavaScript framework (e.g. in a field, view, action, component, ...), because they manage resources, they need to catch errors and inspect them to decide whether the error is critical and the application should crash, or if the error is expected and should be handled in a particular manner."
